** A case against content consumption
  - Wasn't consuming much news the previous week. I have a note on that too. After doing some reflection, and I am optimistic you will come to the same conclusion as I did when you do, there's
   not much difference today between consumption of youtube-op-eds and tiktok consumption. Even when content consumed could probably not be dancing videos, or cat videos. Even when it could
   be about tech. Most of what am getting in my feed is opinions about opinions and takes on real obscure things which after I have learnt about them I never get to put the knowledge to any
   use. That's assuming I even remember what I consumed. I have started putting in, and have been thinking about this for long, conserted effort to narrow consumption to sources I have
   tested to have more signal than noise. That's rare on the internet these days. If you look at the news section for e001 or others , e002 you realise how irrelevant it now feels.  I mean
   maybe to have something to talk about with friends, one would give time to constan news updates. Also, I'm sure you've probably heard the 'dead internet theory' term thrown around. Or, you
   have seen how platforms that used to provide personalised content now seem to skew recommendations towards what you are currently interested in or even worse, what's trending. I looked
   through my subscriptions list and there's a whole lot of channels on there that I haven't gotten an update from (active channels) that have however been active.
   As for hacker news, I still go there every now and then and when I do, I find some good articles.
   
   I have had a list of sources I find myself always returning to. Sources I found real useful the times when I used them or sources I just use often for one reason or another. I
   recently decided to upload a copy of those to my site together with other information. I did that for how easy it is for me to revisit most of what I put on this site. Also, for
   whoever will find it. I am already liking how it is going. The internet , for me at least, does not feel like it has my best interests in mind. It probably once did. But a quick run
   through youtube while I was giving thought to my internet consumption, questioning if I really needed Youtube as much as I thought I did, I noticed most of what was being shown to
   me was things I could do without. And that sentiment I found to be as true for youtube as it was for any other online platform I frequented for "updates". I guess my subconscious
   had already noticed this and its why I moved to upload my sources. I have since been consuming less and less even from people I followed. Most of what is on there is opinions and
   I don't think its healthy to indundate oneself with random opinion 24/7. Trying to train my brain to be more intentional about what I consume (its mostly been whatever the feed
   puts out or whatever the content producer puts out). Its hard but its worth it and with time I am sure it will become my normal. 
   Interesting, and real reassuring (I am not crazy type reassuring), the CEO of some fintech company , Conti, echo's the exact same sentiments. I guess I am onto something here. 

